The assignment `y = x!` should not result in a warning.
```c#
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Runtime.CompilerServices;
[NonNullTypes]
class C
{
    static void F(List<string> x)
    {
        List<string?> y;
        y = x; // warning CS8619: Nullability of 'List<string>' doesn't match 'List<string?>'
        y = x!; // warning CS8619: Nullability of 'List<string>' doesn't match 'List<string?>'
    }
}
```

The second conversion, from `List<string>` to `List<string?>` should result in a warning.
```c#
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Runtime.CompilerServices;
[NonNullTypes]
class C
{
    static void F(List<string> x)
    {
        var y = (List<object>)x;  // error CS0030: Cannot convert 'List<string>' to 'List<object>'
        var z = (List<string?>)x; // no warning
    }
}
```

CodeAnalysis.CSharp.Workspaces 2.6.1 is used.

This the code for my quickfix: 

```

private SyntaxNode CreateSuppressionAttributeSyntax(Diagnostic diagnostic)
{
	var nameSyntax = ParseName(typeof(System.Diagnostics.CodeAnalysis.SuppressMessageAttribute).FullName);
	var argumentList = ParseAttributeArgumentList($@"(""{string.Format(Resources.SuppressMessageCategoryText_0, diagnostic.Id)}"",""{diagnostic.Id}"")");
	var attribute = Attribute(nameSyntax, argumentList);
	return attribute;
}

private async Task<Document> GetTransformedDocumentAsync(CodeFixContext context, CancellationToken cancellationToken, CSharpSyntaxNode attributeTarget, Diagnostic diagnostic)
{
	var documentEditor = await DocumentEditor.CreateAsync(context.Document, cancellationToken);
	var attributeSyntax = CreateSuppressionAttributeSyntax(diagnostic)
				.WithAdditionalAnnotations(new SyntaxAnnotation[]{ Formatter.Annotation, Simplifier.Annotation});
	var modAttrTarget = attributeTarget.WithAdditionalAnnotations(Formatter.Annotation);
	documentEditor.ReplaceNode(attributeTarget, modAttrTarget);
	documentEditor.AddAttribute(modAttrTarget, attributeSyntax);
//		documentEditor.AddAttribute(attributeTarget, attributeSyntax);
	var changedDocument = documentEditor.GetChangedDocument();

	return await Formatter.FormatAsync(changedDocument, context.Document.Project.Solution.Workspace.Options, cancellationToken);
	return changedDocument;
}
```

Note that this codefix works perfectly fine and is formatted correctly when used from within VS without Formatter.FormatAsync.

What i am trying to do here is write my CodeFix in a way where only specific areas are touched by format (my injected attribute and the targetSyntax), so my unit tests are formatted correctly without dealing with trailing+leading whitespace all the time.

If i just use 
```documentEditor.AddAttribute(attributeTarget, attributeSyntax);```

The codefix already does what functionally complete and formatted as intented in VS.

I do not want to use 

```return await Formatter.FormatAsync(changedDocument, context.Document.Project.Solution.Workspace.Options, cancellationToken);```
because that would alter the whole documents formatting.

The reason why i am doing this:
```
var modAttrTarget = attributeTarget.WithAdditionalAnnotations(Formatter.Annotation);
documentEditor.ReplaceNode(attributeTarget, modAttrTarget);
documentEditor.AddAttribute(modAttrTarget, attributeSyntax);
```
is because i am attempting to just mark both the attribute target, as well as the attribute, with formatter annotations so only their formatting is touched - unfortunately when ReplaceNode is executed, for some reason it's throwing an exception telling me "The node is not part of the tree."

Why does `documentEditor.AddAttribute(attributeTarget, attributeSyntax)` work as standalone, if `documentEditor.ReplaceNode(attributeTarget, modAttrTarget)` throws an exception? I don't quite understand that. If the arguments were swapped it would make sense obviously.

